<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / International Company News: American Express may sell life
assurance arm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
American Express, the US financial services and travel group, said it had
retained investment bankers to explore a possible sale of its Amex Life
Assurance unit, which has been approached by several insurers interested in
acquiring the business, Reuter reports.
American Express said it had recently decided that the Amex Life long-term
care insurance business was 'not a critical element in the company's
long-term financial services strategy'.
Amex Life, with about 400 staff, had Dollars 2bn in assets at the end of
1993. 'The interest we are seeing from potential buyers comes at a good
time,' said Mr Thomas Skiff, Amex Life president. 'These insurers see the
potential of this business and the opportunity to capitalise on our position
as the industry leader.'
