<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Government Ethics Row: Minister quits to party relief and
surprise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There was a palpable sense of relief among Conservative MPs yesterday as the
news spread that Mr Neil Hamilton had agreed to resign as corporate affairs
minister.
But there was astonishment when the reason was announced.
Until Mr John Major started his statement to the Commons at 3.30pm it was
widely assumed that Mr Hamilton had been forced to resign because of a
defiant statement issued to local newspapers in Cheshire.
The prime minister's revelation that he had agreed to resign because the
impact of fresh allegations made on Monday 'disables him from carrying out
his responsibilities' stunned MPs on both sides of the House.
Mr Hamilton, a colourful rightwinger, had earlier appeared determined to
fight on against allegations that he asked Commons questions for Mr Mohamed
Fayed, the owner of Harrods, in return for cash and a week at the Paris
Ritz.
Mr Hamilton said in his statement: 'Since my appointment as a DTI minister I
have sought to undertake my responsibilities with scrupulous integrity and I
am dismayed by and resent these wild and false accusations.'
He said he had asked just three parliamentary questions relating to Mr
Fayed's House of Fraser and three relating to Lonrho - which had also sought
to purchase Harrods - after the trip to the Ritz.
The questions were prompted by a long-standing interest in competition
policy and 'my sympathy for House of Fraser's position', he said.
Mr Hamilton said he was advised when he became corporate affairs minister in
1992 that there was no legal reason why he should not perform ministerial
functions in relation to House of Fraser.
But 'in view of my partisan involvement . . . I specifically instructed my
officials that they were not to show me any papers relevant to the House of
Fraser, not to involve me in meetings, and to have any ministerial decisions
made by other ministers', he said.
Mr Hamilton's comments on the allegations were regarded by most Tory MPs as
typically robust. But there was widespread dismay and embarrassment about
his reasons for refusing to leave office to pursue a libel action against
The Guardian.
He said: 'Of course I could resign and fight a libel action from the back
benches. But the same argument could have applied to the prime minister in
respect of his action against the scurrilous Scallywag magazine, or against
other ministers who have fought libel actions.
'There is no reason whatsoever why a minister of the crown should not remain
in office whilst undertaking libel proceedings. Indeed the prime minister
did just that - and quite rightly so,' he said.
'In Britain, it is the established principle that a person is innocent
unless proved guilty. It is for the courts to decide upon these matters, not
the media or indeed anyone else.'
This appeared to have sealed Mr Hamilton's fate as a minister. In
particular, Tory MPs were aghast at his reference to Mr Major's successful
libel action against the New Statesman magazine, which reported unfounded
allegations in Scallywag that the prime minister had had an affair with a
Downing Street caterer, Ms Clare Latimer.
When it emerged in mid-morning that Mr Hamilton had cancelled an engagement
and was returning to London, it was widely assumed that he was about to be
sacked for issuing the statement without government approval.
In fact, Mr Hamilton had been called not to Number 10 but to Number 12
Downing Street, the home of Mr Richard Ryder, the government chief whip.
He was informed of the fresh allegations and agreed immediately to step
down.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
