<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Equities lower on drift by
bonds, dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Most US share prices finished lower yesterday after stocks paralleled a
uncertain drift by bonds, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
By the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 4.71 at 3,850.59,
but the more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was up 0.69 at 461.52.
Despite its slight gain, declining issues on the NYSE led advances by a
two-to-one margin, on heavy volume of 326m shares.
In the other leading markets, the Nasdaq composite closed down 2.95 at
758.26 and the American SE composite dipped 0.88 to 452.85.
The Dow industrials began with a 16-point deficit, but managed to crawl back
to their starting point by mid-morning thanks to some improvement in the
bond market.
Longer dated Treasuries, which were carrying their highest yields and lowest
prices in more than two years, appreciated on the Conference Board's
announcement that consumer confidence had sagged last month. But the ensuing
bargain-hunting quickly petered out, and concerns over the weak dollar and
monetary policy soon reasserted themselves. The blue chips began to slump
anew, only to claw most of their way back by the close.
Some stocks performed well, however, largely in response to a generally
favourable tranche of earnings news.
The second round of results from the energy group produced a few pleasant
surprises. Texaco, one of the Dow components, gained Dollars 7/8 to Dollars
63 after it posted third-quarter net income of 98 cents, about 25 per cent
better than analysts had forecast. Exxon, another Dow industrial, earned a
late reward for better-than-expected results revealed during the previous
session. The stock climbed Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 60 3/8 .
But it was Mobil, up Dollars 3 to Dollars 83 1/4 , which fared the best
among the oil companies. Dean Witter Reynolds lifted its rating on the stock
as the company completed a study on ways to cut costs and restructure its
operations.
USX-US Steel was marked down Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 36 3/8 even though its
third quarter net, published after Monday's close, jumped to Dollars 1.11
from 41 cents a year earlier.
By contrast, Eastman Kodak escaped unscathed after it posted earnings of 57
cents, well under forecast. The stock added Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 48,
though it had fallen by nearly 11 per cent since mid-September on
anticipation of just such a result.
Sprint, the long-distance telephone company, slumped Dollars 1 1/2 3 to
Dollars 33 1/4 after announcing a joint venture with Tele-Communications,
Comcast and Cox Enterprises.
In pharmaceuticals, Baxter International lost Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 25 on
news that its third quarter net had fallen short of Wall Street
expectations.
Dr Pepper/Seven-Up jumped Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 24 1/2 on the revelation
of talks over a possible acquisition of the soft-drinks company by Cadbury
Schweppes, whose ADRs receded Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 28 1/4 on the Nasdaq.
</TEXT>
