<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / International Company News: Recovery at RJR Nabisco
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RJR Nabisco's earnings bounced in the third quarter, marking a recovery from
the price war that rocked the US tobacco industry a year ago.
The group recorded continuing advances in sales in its international tobacco
business, particularly in Eastern Europe, and in US biscuit sales.
The rebound in earnings, to 11 cents a share from 4 cents a year ago, met
market expectations. It comes as Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, an investment
firm, is seeking to use part of its RJR stake to buy Borden, another food
group.
Overall operating profits rose by Dollars 248m to Dollars 835m. US tobacco
operations, which earned Dollars 382m, accounted for Dollars 181m of this
improvement.
The recovery stemmed in part from a 5 per cent increase in sales, as RJR
switched its product mix towards higher-value brands such as Winston, Camel
and Salem.
Sales growth in Russia and eastern Europe was the main factor behind a 12
per cent increase in international tobacco revenues.
Operating earnings in the food businesses reached Dollars 285m, up from
Dollars 230m, as North American earnings were boosted by higher sales at
Nabisco.
Overall net income was Dollars 216m on sales of nearly Dollars 4bn, compared
with Dollars 76m on sales of Dollars 3.6bn a year ago.
</TEXT>
