<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / International Company News: Nortel benefits from
restructuring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Northern Telecom, the Canadian telecommunications equipment maker, is
starting to see the benefits of its restructuring and growing exposure to
overseas markets.
Highlights of the Toronto-based company's third-quarter earnings included a
2 per cent improvement in margins, and a rising share of the market for
office switchboards (PBXs). Revenues grew by 6 per cent, in spite of the
disposal of several businesses last year and a substantial decline in
revenues from Canada.
Net earnings were USDollars 56m, or 22 cents a share, compared with a loss
of Dollars 35m, or 13 cents a share, a year earlier. Earnings were boosted
by a Dollars 43m, one-time jump in investment income.
Revenues advanced to just over Dollars 2bn from Dollars 1.88bn. Northern
told analysts yesterday that revenues would have risen by 14 per cent if
divested businesses were included.
New orders in the quarter slipped to Dollars 1.95bn from Dollars 2.34bn a
year earlier. 'We don't view this with any alarm,' a Northern official said.
Customers have indicated that their order cycles are shortening. The company
forecast higher orders in the traditionally strong fourth quarter.
The improved margins were ascribed to cost cutting, and to a more profitable
product mix, such as high-margin PBXs.
Northern told analysts that catch-up work on its transmission software was
now a week ahead of schedule. Delays in this area contributed to a slide in
investor confidence early last year. But its share price has recovered
sharply since then.
The shares were down 50 cents at CDollars 48.50 in early trading on the
Toronto stock exchange, compared with last year's low of about CDollars 30.
One analyst said that he was encouraged by Northern's growing emphasis on
broadband 'information highway' products and on fast-growing overseas
markets, such as Latin America, China and Taiwan.
</TEXT>
