FT  26 OCT 94 / International Company News: Shell Canada ahead sharply at
nine months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Strong domestic and export markets for chemicals, oil and natural gas and
sulphur brought a sharp turnround in Shell Canada's third-quarter and
nine-month results.
Net profit in the third quarter was CDollars 89m (USDollars 65.81m), or 79
cents a share, up from CDollars 1m, or 1 cent (after a CDollars 32m special
charge), in the 1993 period. Revenues for the company, a subsidiary of the
Royal Dutch Shell group, were CDollars 1.35bn against CDollars 1.17bn.
Nine months' profit was CDollars 217m, or CDollars 1.93, up from CDollars
13m, or 11 cents, on revenues of CDollars 3.7bn against CDollars 3.48bn.
Cash flow from operations was CDollars 561m against CDollars 377m.
The resource sector provided most of the gain, but refining margins
recovered and a sharp rise in contributions from chemicals came mainly from
stronger styrene prices.
Canada's biggest integrated oil company Imperial Oil (70 per cent owned by
Exxon of the US) posted third-quarter net profit of CDollars 171m, or 88
cents a share, up from CDollars 84m, or 43 cents, a year earlier, with
better upstream and downstream contributions. Nine months' profit was
CDollars 258m, or CDollars 1.33, up 15 per cent from a year earlier.
Revenues were CDollars 6.67bn, little changed.
