<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / International Company News: Eastman Kodak declines further
despite sales rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Eastman Kodak, the US photographic manufacturer, announced a further decline
in operating profit in the third quarter and said restructuring of the
company might be necessary in the fourth quarter.
Profits from the company's imaging business, which forms almost its sole
activity after an Dollars 8bn disposal programme, were down 25 per cent in
the quarter in spite of a 12 per cent rise in sales.
Net earnings fell 33 per cent to Dollars 193m, or Dollars 0.57 a share,
excluding last year's restructuring charge of Dollars 353m. Kodak said
charges stemming from the write-down of assets - principally stocks - had
cost 12 cents a share in the quarter. First-time consolidation of its Qualex
photo-finishing business had cost a further 6 cents a share. Before Qualex's
contribution, group sales were up 8 per cent.
Kodak's shares, which had largely discounted the news, closed up Dollars
1/8 at Dollars 48 in New York. The shares are about 11 per cent off their
peak in mid-September, when the market was enthusiastic about the rapid
progress being made in asset disposals by Mr George Fisher, the new
chairman.
The company said yesterday that besides its stock problems, it had been
affected by pricing pressures and cost increases in advertising,
administration and employment benefits.
Mr Fisher, who described the results as mixed, said: 'Our cost management
efforts continued during the third quarter and will carry into the fourth
quarter . . . Kodak will not inventory its problems and carry them forward.
We will emerge from 1994 with a strong balance sheet and a solid benchmark
for measuring future performance'.
The commercial imaging division suffered a particularly sharp profits fall
of 39 per cent in the quarter to Dollars 94m, with margins down to 4.9 per
cent from 8.5 per cent. Performance in copiers was hit by sluggish sales,
Kodak said. Profits from consumer imaging were down 19 per cent to Dollars
269m, with margins down to 16.7 per cent from 24.6 per cent.
Kodak said it was 'hard to speculate' on the size of any restructuring
programme, since nothing had yet been decided. Last year's Dollars 353m
restructuring programme came before Mr Fisher's arrival, it pointed out.
</TEXT>
