<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / UK Company News: Wolseley shows rise of 67%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Wolseley, the world's biggest supplier of heating and plumbing equipment,
lifted annual profits 67 per cent after a strong performance from all
divisions and good contributions from acquisitions.
Pre-tax profits for the year to July 31 were at the top end of analysts'
expectations at Pounds 202.3m, up from Pounds 121.1m. Turnover rose by 31
per cent from Pounds 2.49bn to Pounds 3.25bn.
Mr Jeremy Lancaster, chairman and managing director, said the results from
the divisions across Europe and the US had an element of Alice in Wonderland
 -'everyone has won and everyone deserves prizes'.
The biggest gain came from the US, where profits from building distribution
leapt from Pounds 47m to Pounds 86.8m on turnover up from Pounds 1.21bn to
Pounds 1.72bn. The first full contribution from Erb Lumber, acquired last
September, was Pounds 13.5m.
Mr Lancaster said Erb and Carolina Builders, both lumber distributors, had
been 'on a roll for two years' with 30 per cent annual sales growth, but the
rate would slow this year.
In Europe, profits from building distribution improved from Pounds 57.1m to
Pounds 81m on sales up from Pounds 1bn to Pounds 1.14bn.
The UK, where the group has 444 outlets, performed strongly, but Wolseley
warned that the British recovery was fragile, and that it was impossible to
predict the housing market.
The manufacturing division lifted profits from Pounds 26.8m to Pounds 36.6m
on turnover up from Pounds 278.5m to Pounds 390.3m including a good first
full contribution from Enertech, the Swedish oil and gas burner
manufacturer.
Net debt at the end of the year fell from Pounds 62.3m to Pounds 56.3m,
leaving gearing at 10.1 per cent (14.7 per cent). Net interest payable fell
from Pounds 9.8m to Pounds 2.1m. Earnings per share rose from 33.60p to
50.77p.
Wolseley proposes to raise the final dividend from 9.75p to 12p a share, to
take the total for the year to 16.72p (13.30p).
The board, which is offering a scrip alternative for the first time, is also
proposing a one-for-one scrip issue.
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
