<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / UK Company News: Salomon Brothers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Salomon Brothers, the US investment bank, has become a substantial
preference shareholder in Attwoods, the waste management company fighting
off a Pounds 364m bid from Browning-Ferris Industries of the US.
After buying an initial 1m preference shares at 88 1/2 p last week, Salomon
disclosed yesterday that it had paid a further Pounds 3.2m for 3.64m prefs,
at 88p, bringing the its total stake to 7.3 per cent. This is 3p higher than
the price offered by BFI's offer. and has left many dealers puzzled as to
the bank's motives. Salomon bought some of the prefs from Fidelity
Investments, which remains a substantial ordinary shareholder.
Yet Under the offer, A successful BFI has would have the right in certain
circumstances to demand early conversion of the prefs, or redemption at
100p. once it controlled 75 per cent of the preference shares. While Laidlaw
of Canada has already agreed to sell its 73 per cent pref stake to BFI. at
85p. there is no guarantee that BFI would demand redemption.
</TEXT>
