<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Observer: Dayly grind
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord Howe may be the last of the Thatcher government's troika to publish his
memoirs, but he could be the first to stage a political comeback - if you
listen to Sir Robin Day, the veteran TV interviewer. Sir Robin, attending
the launch of Lord Howe's book, confidently predicted that Howe would soon
be back in government as Lord Chancellor, giving it some 'much-needed
bottom'.
Then again, Sir Robin might be a bit biased. The two of them go back a long
way. Both were called to the Bar on the same evening in 1952 and both stood
for Parliament in 1959. Sir Robin and Geoffrey Howe failed, but it was at
that election that Maggie Thatcher first became an MP. 'I disappeared into
the obscurity of the TV studios . . . such is the way the destiny of great
nations is decided,' joked Sir Robin.
</TEXT>
