<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ITV launches a new drama series called Ellington (starring Chris Ellison in
the title role, just to be thoroughly confusing) with a 90-minute pilot. We
are told that Ellington is a sports promoter and personal manager who
'maintains his integrity and sense of fair play as he battles his way
through the corruption'. We are assured that, although he was raised in 'the
tough and shady environment of smoke-filled snooker halls and dingy boxing
gymnasia' Ellington is 'a survivor'. Well well. Presumably it will be, you
know, gritty? (8.30). Yet another documentary about yet another nasty small
group on the extreme right wing of British politics: Dispatches investigates
an organisation which it says has been linked to the British National Party,
'Combat 18', whose members, it is asserted, make threatening phone calls,
smash windows, make death threats, tamper with cars and put offensive
material through letter boxes (9.00 C4). The acting in Between The Lines is
still good, the writing is competent, but the series has lost its edge since
Tony and Harry left the Met (9.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
