<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Management: Open to suggestion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Company suggestion schemes can pay handsome dividends if the arrangements
are well packaged and backed by attractive rewards for employees.
A study carried out by the Industrial Society* found that companies which
have taken dusty suggestions boxes down from the walls and revamped their
schemes are benefiting from a stream of new ideas.
The society has produced an information pack for employers which includes
guidance and examples of successful schemes from 12 organisations. Some of
the more productive schemes include:
Land Rover's relaunched scheme. This reaped suggestions worth Pounds 2m in
its first year. One suggestion that less fuel should be put in the tanks to
drive cars from the production line saved Pounds 25,000 a year and earned
Pounds 5,000 for the employee who suggested it.
In the Rover parent company a suggestion that industrial gloves could be
recycled saved the group more than Pounds 100,000 a year. The staff member
who made the suggestion received Pounds 5,000.
Another Pounds 5,000 was awarded to a woman who suggested an alternative
printing process to replace the need to laminate the covers of car
handbooks. That saved Pounds 30,000 a year.
Midland Bank's Bright Ideas scheme. Subsequent proposals saved more than
Pounds 250,000.
East Midland's Eureka scheme. This helped save Pounds 22,000. Some Pounds
5,000 has been paid out in rewards to staff.
'Suggestion schemes are vital because they encourage innovation, quality and
cost savings,' says the Industrial Society's Georgina Tate. 'Good schemes
promote employee involvement and commitment.'
*The suggestions scheme information pack is available, price Pounds 35, from
the Industrial Society information service. Tel 071 262 2401.
</TEXT>
