<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Government Ethics Row: Inquiry puts MPs' little earners in
the spotlight - The remit of the latest investigation of standards in public
life
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major, the prime minister, said yesterday that his proposed
committee of inquiry was the 'widest-ranging inquiry into standards in
public life since the second world war'.
This is a dubious claim. A royal commission sat for two years in the 1970s
to investigate standards of conduct in public life.
As with Mr Major's inquiry, it was chaired by a law lord, Lord Salmon,
included nominees of the main political parties and non-party experts, and
had a remit incorporating central government, local government and other
public bodies.
The background to the Salmon commission was the Poulson affair - a
long-running case of sleaze far more serious than any yet alleged in public
by Mr Mohamed Fayed, or by those critical of the activities of unelected
quangos.
For nearly 20 years Mr John Poulson's architecture and construction empire
manipulated a web of corrupt officials in local government, the police and
the National Health Service, which was revealed when he went bankrupt in
1972. Mr Poulson and several local councillors and officials were convicted
of corruption.
The Salmon commission was concerned mainly with corruption in local
government. It recommended a range of reforms, notably declarations and
registers of interest, which have since been instituted.
It is the breach of the rules governing one such register of interests -
that for MPs - which is a key issue in the present controversy.
The Salmon report had little to say about central government and the
Commons, which were only incidental to the Poulson affair, or about the way
appointments were made to public bodies. It accepted implicitly that
parliament should regulate itself.
Lord Nolan's committee will not start with the same assumptions. It faces
calls from across the political spectrum for MPs to be subject to some form
of code of conduct, and growing unease about the way appointments are made
to public bodies.
Lord Nolan said last night that he supported hearings that were in public.
He said: 'I've grown up doing my work in open court in public and that is
how I would prefer to go forward.'
As Lord Justice Nolan he assisted in the Appeal Court decision which found
Mr Kenneth Baker, then home secretary, guilty of contempt after he failed to
respond to an order to return an unlawfully deported asylum-seeker to
Britain.
Lord Nolan's committee has six months to grapple with a range of issues. The
most important are:
MPs and outside interests. Until recently few questioned the right of MPs to
accept paid work outside the Commons. Indeed the practice is widely defended
as desirable to give MPs a feel for the 'outside world' and to supplement a
salary - now Pounds 31,687 - below that which many enjoyed before they were
elected. The question has been the disclosure of outside payments.
There are now calls for tighter rules to be placed on outside interests. Mr
Vernon Bogdanor, reader in government at Oxford University, said: 'The Nolan
committee needs to look carefully at whether MPs should have outside
incomes. Their job is to serve their constituents, and it is a bogus
argument to claim that they can only learn about the 'outside world' by
being a paid consultant.'
The implications are stark. More than than 200 MPs out of the 651 are
employed as parliamentary consultants to lobbying companies and other
commercial organisations - often at a fee of Pounds 10,000 or more per
consultancy per year.
The appointment of members of public bodies. Ministers have largely
unfettered discretion over appointments they make to public bodies. Until
1979, however, ministers generally offered fair representation to the main
opposition party.
The breakdown of this tacit agreement accounts for much of the current
acrimony. Entrenched in office, the governments of Mrs Thatcher and Mr Major
have paid less regard to the claims of opposition parties for appointments.
The resentment has been exacerbated by the growth of quangos, such as NHS
trusts, strongly opposed by Labour.
Options for change include placing obligations on ministers to offer a
certain proportion of appointments to opposition parties, or the
establishment of a vetting body to ensure the quality and fairness of
appointments.
Complaints against MPs. Members of the public aggrieved with their local
council - or with many other public bodies - can appeal to an ombudsman.
There is no such recourse for those dissatisfied with the service given to
them by their MP - or for those who believe that their MP is not declaring
his or her interests.
One reform which has attracted support would be to establish an ombudsman to
oversee the work of MPs - perhaps in conjunction with a formal code of
conduct.
Any such move would probably be opposed by MPs. Since King Charles I's
attempts to arrest five MPs in 1642 they have fought tenaciously against any
form of outside interference.
</TEXT>
