<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Government Ethics Row: Tories accused on health trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Margaret Beckett, shadow health secretary, last night accused the
government of packing hospital trusts with supporters of the Conservative
party and privatising the National Health Service by stealth.
She said 66 of the self-governing trusts were chaired either by a Tory or by
someone connected with a company which had made donations to the
Conservative party.
The charges were strongly rebutted in the Commons by Mrs Virginia Bottomley,
health secretary, who confirmed that the trusts could be examined by the new
committee which was to scrutinise the standards of conduct of all holders of
public office.
Mrs Bottomley said that the outcome would be a recognition that the new
management bodies established in the NHS were 'models to follow'.
Mrs Beckett called for a central register of quangos and a register listing
every NHS trust board member and their qualifications.
The shadow health secretary, who branded Mrs Bottomley the 'Madame Mao' of
the health service, said trust boards were overwhelmingly packed with
'representatives of Conservative interests'.
One third of the places were held by directors of private companies, while
others were filled by solicitors and accountants. Only 4 per cent to 6 per
cent of those appointed had experience of the NHS.
The government won a majority of 34 (297-263) to defeat a Labour motion
endorsing 'public alarm' at the creeping privatisation of the NHS.
</TEXT>
