<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Government Ethics Row: Hamilton forced out by 'foul rumour'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Neil Hamilton, the former corporate affairs minister, said last night
that he had been forced to quit the government by 'foully motivated rumour
and a media witchhunt'.
Mr Hamilton said in a bitter letter to Mr John Major that the events
surrounding the prime minister's demand that he leave the government were
'sad and deeply disturbing'.
He said he had conducted himself with 'integrity and due regard for
propriety and probity' and had received no payments from Mr Mohamed Fayed,
the owner of Harrods.
Mr Hamilton thanked Mr Major for confirming in the Commons that allegations
of impropriety made against him were unsubstantiated. He said he would clear
his name.
In his response Mr Major said he was sorry for the way Mr Hamilton's
ministerial career had ended and praised his work at the Department of Trade
and Industry. He said: 'I am grateful to you for the readiness with which
you recognised that it was impossible for you to continue in government in
the circumstances.'
The letters were released amid a mixture of relief among mainstream
Conservatives and anger among rightwingers. MPs on all sides were confused
by the day's events.
Initially it was assumed Mr Hamilton had been forced to quit because of a
defiant statement issued to newspapers in his Cheshire constituency.
The prime minister's disclosure to the Commons that he had agreed to resign
because of the impact of fresh allegations made on Monday stunned MPs.
At no time yesterday did Mr Major detail the new allegations against Mr
Hamilton, but senior government sources confirmed they did not relate to Mr
Hamilton's connection with Mr Fayed.
Mr John Carlisle, the MP for Luton North, said: 'The prime minister is
attempting to resurrect a situation which has gone a bit out of control, but
I don't agree with the way he has gone about it.'
Mr Alan Duncan, another rightwinger, said: 'He was a colourful and a
competent minister. There is a sad irony that he has gone on the day that
the spotlight has moved to the questionable conduct of the man who accused
him.'
Mr Hamilton, a witty rightwinger, had earlier appeared determined to fight
on against allegations that he asked Commons questions for Mr Fayed in
return for cash and a week at the Paris Ritz.
In a statement issued in his constituency he said he was dismayed by the
'wild and false accusations' against him - comments regarded by most Tory
MPs as typically robust.
But there was widespread dismay and embarrassment about his reasons for
refusing to leave office to pursue a libel action against The Guardian.
He said: 'Of course I could resign and fight a libel action from the back
benches. But the same argument could have applied to the prime minister in
respect of his action against the scurrilous Scallywag magazine, or against
other ministers who have fought libel actions.
'There is no reason whatsoever why a minister of the crown should not remain
in office whilst undertaking libel proceedings. Indeed the prime minister
did just that - and quite rightly so,' he said.
Many Tory MPs were aghast at his reference to Mr Major's successful libel
action against the New Statesman magazine, which reported unfounded
allegations in Scallywag that the prime minister had had an extra-marital
affair.
When it emerged in mid-morning that Mr Hamilton had cancelled an engagement
and was returning to London it was widely assumed that he was about to be
sacked for issuing the statement without government approval.
In fact, Mr Hamilton was summoned by Mr Richard Ryder, government chief
whip. He was informed of the fresh allegations and agreed to quit.
</TEXT>
