<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Banks given Maxwell deadline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
International investment banks and advisers to the pension schemes formerly
controlled by the late Robert Maxwell have been given until November 4 to
make an offer of restitution, Norma Cohen writes.
Sir Peter Webster, the former High Court judge appointed to help find a
'global solution' to the shortfall in Maxwell pension scheme assets, met
trustees and advisers to most of the schemes yesterday. Sir Peter said he
hoped the plan would raise enough for each scheme to meet its liabilities in
full.
Sir Peter has been working since last spring to find ways of allowing
investment banks and advisers to make restitution without implicitly
admitting wrongdoing.
Those which do not make reasonable offers by November 4 risk legal action by
the pension schemes. It is understood that several schemes have prepared
writs, which have not yet been served, seeking millions of pounds.
Sir Peter is understood to have told trustees that participants in the
solution are likely to set conditions on their contributions. In particular,
they will seek confidentiality and a guarantee that no further claims be
made against them.
</TEXT>
