<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / London-wide co-ordination of buses urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Some central control of London's buses will still be needed after
privatisation to ensure that they continue to provide an efficient service,
the Chartered Institute of Transport said yesterday.
The institute, which represents people working in the transport sector, said
in a report that priority measures such as special bus lanes would need to
be co-ordinated on a London-wide basis by local authorities and the bus
companies.
There would also be a pivotal role for London Transport in setting standards
for infrastructure such as stations, stops and shelters, in providing
passenger information, and supervising ticketing arrangements which allow
passengers to make journeys on buses owned by different companies.
Six of the 10 companies which make up London Buses have been sold in the
past two months. Completion of privatisation is expected before the end of
the year.
The institute said local authorities should adopt traffic schemes which gave
priority to buses. This would increase bus use, reduce congestion and cut
environmental pollution.
It urged the government to modify the system of tendering for bus contracts.
When an existing operator lost a contract it could face large redundancy
costs. The institute suggested that 'some marginal preference' for existing
operators could provide for greater continuity without discouraging
competitive bids for routes.
Whither the Clapham Omnibus. The Future for Buses in London. CIT, 80
Portland Place, London W1N 4DP. Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
