<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Scientists predict tiny processors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Researchers yesterday announced a breakthrough in electronic miniaturisation
which could lead to computer memories and microprocessors 500 times faster
than today's silicon chips and one-five hundredth the size.
Scientists at Toshiba Cambridge Research Centre and Cambridge University
have developed the world's first process for making 'quantum effect
integrated circuits'. These devices consist of millions of microscopically
small components on a chip the size of a fingernail.
Professor Michael Pepper, managing director of the research centre, said
that the achievement was of comparable significance to the discovery in 1958
of the technology for making integrated circuits on silicon instead of
connecting together individual transistors. That breakthrough led to the
information technology revolution which started in the early 1970s and is
still gathering pace.
Many electronics laboratories have made such microscopic components,
including 'quantum wires' one-hundred thousandth the thickness of human
hair. But their individual production is painstakingly slow and expensive.
The microscopic components - no more than 10 atoms across - are so small
that the electrons in them behave both as particles and waves, in accordance
with the bizarre predictions of quantum theory. This allows the circuits to
switch far faster than those in conventional chips.
The Toshiba process makes it possible to mass produce them on integrated
circuits like conventional chips. The process has several stages and is
technically complex, but Prof Pepper said it was 'highly manufacturable and
could readily be transferred to a production environment' at reasonable
cost.
The main technical barrier to overcome is that the quantum devices can only
operate when cooled in liquid helium to temperatures close to absolute zero.
Scientists can, however, foresee them being developed to work at room
temperature.
Chips based on the technology could reach the market in about 10 years.
There are many possible applications, including super-fast memory and logic
circuits for computers and more precisely controllable lasers.
Mr Sei-Ichi Takayanagi, Toshiba's senior adviser on research, said the
technology was still too far from the market to transfer to the company's
Japanese research and development laboratories. It would be developed in
Cambridge for about five years - and licensed to any other companies that
wanted to use it.
Prof Pepper predicted that many new applications would emerge which no one
had yet thought of. He said: 'Think of all the changes in computing and
communications in the last 25 years, and try to extrapolate those 25 years
ahead.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
