<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Unpopular counties killed off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Avon and Humberside county councils, two creations of the 1974
reorganisation, will be abolished in 1996 as part of the local government
review.
The announcement, made yesterday by Mr John Gummer, environment secretary,
had been widely predicted, as the 1974 counties were thought to be
unpopular.
Unitary authorities, combining the powers now held by county and district
councils, will be formed in their place. In Avon, Bristol will become a
unitary council, while Bath will merge with the surrounding Wandsdyke
district, and Northavon with Kingswood, to form new merged unitaries.
Woodspring district, centred on Weston-super-Mare, will become a unitary on
its current boundaries.
In Humberside Mr Gummer has slightly altered the proposals made by the Local
Government Commission. Hull will become a unitary council, as seems likely
to happen with most of England's provincial cities, but Mr Gummer suggests
that its present boundaries should be extended, a provision not made by the
commission.
The remainder of Humberside north of the Humber will become one large
unitary, to be known as East Yorkshire.
South of the Humber the towns of Scunthorpe and Grimsby will merge with the
more rural district councils that surround them to form two new unitaries.
In North Yorkshire Mr Gummer has made significant changes to the blueprint
presented to him by the commission. York will be given extended boundaries
and become a unitary, in line with the commission's propo-sals.
But the proposal to amalgamate all the other districts of North Yorkshire
into two unitary 'ridings' has been dropped, after fierce opposition from
local MPs. Instead, North Yorkshire outside York will continue with two
tiers as at present. Proposals to merge Goole with Yorkshire have also been
dropped.
In Somerset the commission's proposal to create three unitary authorities
has been abandoned, while Mr Gummer did not to ask the commission to
reconsider its proposal that Lincolnshire should remain untouched, with two
tiers of local government.
Nine unitary authorities will be created, with a total population of
slightly more than 1.9m. The commission said that the counties of Avon and
Humberside had 'never been supported generally by local residents, who
clearly wanted change'.
Mr Gummer defended the decision to create unitaries in some areas but to
leave two tiers intact elsewhere.
Compulsory competitive tendering of English local authorities' information
technology services has been postponed by a year and will not now start
until October 1997, the Department of the Environment announced yesterday.
At that point metropolitan authorities and councils which avoid
reorganisation in the local government review must expose 70 per cent by
value of their information technology work to competition.
</TEXT>
