<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Elected 'senate' to unite engineering profession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The 13-year-old Engineering Council is to be replaced with an elected
'senate', creating a united engineering profession.
Yesterday's announcement is an important breakthrough in a three-year battle
by Sir John Fairclough, chairman of the council.
Sir John announced a proposal that would create a body to bring together the
views of the institutions, industry and academia and provide a single voice
for the profession.
The plan was warmly welcomed last night by Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and
industry secretary.
Mr Heseltine said: 'A unified body will give the engineering profession the
single influential voice it badly needs.'
The council is the umbrella body for 41 professional institutions, but many
engineers believe it has failed to provide an effective voice for the
profession. Bigger institutions have been wary of conceding too much power
to it.
After several months of discussions in a policy group set up in September
last year the breakthrough came with the development of a proposal for a
democratically elected 'senate' to be the focal point for the profession.
The senate would have two boards, one for the regulation of the profession
and the other for its promotion. Board members would be selected from the
54-strong senate, 24 of whose members would be elected by institution
councils from their past and present council members, 24 by engineers and
technicians, and six appointed by the Privy Council.
The proposals have been unanimously endorsed by the policy group, and by a
meeting of the council of institution presidents. Sir John said yesterday:
'I am very optimistic.' He hopes that all the institutions will sign a
declaration supporting the proposal by the end of January, allowing the new
arrangements to be in place by the middle of next year.
It will have to appoint a director-general. Mr Denis Filer, the council's
director-general, who is due to have retired, is to see the council through
its transition.
</TEXT>
