FT  26 OCT 94 / Consumer bad debt problems reduced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bad debt problems among consumers are receding, says a survey by credit
information group Equifax Europe, Philip Coggan writes.
The survey found that 7.1 per cent of instalment credit accounts were in
arrears in the third quarter, down from 9 per cent in the same period last
year.
There was a smaller fall in accounts significantly in arrears - defined as
those three or more months behind in payments - to 3.5 per cent in the third
quarter from 3.7 per cent in the same period last year.
Equifax's figures cover instalment credit, including credit cards, from
finance houses, banks, building societies and other businesses such as the
motor trade.
According to the survey Northern Ireland is the region with the lowest level
of bad debt, with only 5.6 per cent of consumers in arrears.
Scotland has the highest bad-debt level, with 8.4 per cent of consumers
behind with payments.
