<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / BT3 share sale methods backed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Audit Office, the public-spending watchdog, yesterday endorsed
the methods used by investment bank SG Warburg to co-ordinate the sale of
the government's remaining stake in British Telecommunications last year.
The tactics attracted strong criticism from institutions. They objected to
Warburg's efforts to prevent the sale of new shares to those who disposed of
shares or sold shares they did not own immediately before the BT3 global
offering.
Warburg had used a variation of the so-called global bookbuilding technique,
in which the price at which the new shares are sold reflects market demand
on the day of the offering. There have been suggestions that in similar
bookbuilding operations in London investors manipulated share prices by
dumping stock or selling short immediately before pricing. This would have
allowed them to buy the new shares more cheaply.
Warburg tried to ensure that those who had recently sold BT shares were not
allocated new shares.
The study found that Warburg won 36 per cent of the Pounds 20m of
commissions from the international portion of the offering, down from 41 per
cent of commissions on BT2.
The watchdog praised the techniques used in the BT3 offering, and said that
77 of 78 institutional investors interviewed regarded the sale as a success.
Sir John Bourn, comptroller and auditor-general, said the sale had raised
Pounds 5.2bn, in line with Treasury expectations.
</TEXT>
