<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Balladur-Chirac duel descends into farce
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Such is now the intensity of political rivalry inside France's ruling
Gaullist RPR party that every move by the prime minister, Mr Edouard
Balladur, or by Mr Jacques Chirac, the party leader, is automatically
interpreted as part of their deadly duel to win the Elysee.
The fact that Mr Balladur cancelled a meeting yesterday with RPR deputies
was widely interpreted as a move to dodge confrontation with backbench MPs
complaining at his criticism of Mr Chirac.
Mr Balladur himself explained that he had found time to meet RPR senators
yesterday, but not the deputies, because, though he was pressed for time, he
had a long-standing appointment to meet the former group.
But his side-stepping of the deputies may have also had something to do with
the fact the latter included Mr Chirac, an MP for the Correze region as well
as mayor of Paris, and who had decided to delay a trip to Tokyo for several
hours to attend the meeting. This prompted speculation about whether it was
Mr Balladur who cancelled, on learning Mr Chirac had altered his travel
plans, or vice versa.
All that this farce can be safely held to illustrate is the extraordinary
allergy that has developed between France's prime minister and the leader of
his own party.
Despite all the calls by themselves and their party for unity, the two men
seem to like being as far apart as possible. These days, for instance, Mr
Chirac likes to be out of Paris on Tuesdays when Mr Balladur hosts a weekly
meeting of the conservative coalition's leaders.
One possible way of settling the Balladur-Chirac rivalry would be to hold
US-style primary elections, as urged by Mr Charles Pasqua, the RPR interior
minister. But acceptance of this proposal is unlikely.
The former French president, Mr Valery Giscard d'Estaing, said yesterday
that rivalries on the right were no obstacle to winning the presidency. He
noted that the right had three times fielded two rival candidates since 1958
and won.
Meanwhile, Mr Alain Carignon, who resigned from the Balladur government to
fight corruption allegations, was yesterday remanded in custody at least
until October 28, while at the same time a former close associate of his at
the Grenoble city hall made fresh accusations in yesterday's Liberation
newspaper that Mr Carignon had promised the city's water concession to
Lyonnaise des Eaux.
French blood sport, Page 22
</TEXT>
