<HEADLINE>
FT  26 OCT 94 / Major orders probe into rules for public life
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major ordered a sweeping investigation into standards in public life
yesterday after the mounting allegations of sleaze in his government forced
the second ministerial resignation within a week.
During a day of high drama at Westminster, Mr Neil Hamilton, the industry
minister named last week as the recipient of hospitality from the Harrods
owner Mr Mohamed Fayed, was forced by Mr Major to quit the government.
But Mr Major's attempt to regain the initiative failed to dispel the
political controversy engulfing his government and brought charges from Mr
Tony Blair, the Labour leader, that he was in the thrall of events outside
of his control.
In a bitter resignation letter to the prime minister Mr Hamilton left no
doubt that he had left the government unwillingly. He said: 'I think it is
sad and deeply disturbing that I have been forced to leave office because of
foully motivated rumour and a media witch hunt.'
Mr Hamilton's dismissal also provoked unconcealed rage among his supporters
on the Tory right. They accused Mr Major of caving in to media pressure.
Despite an expression of support for the government in his resignation
letter, his friends said Mr Hamilton would prove a dangerous enemy on the
backbenches.
Mr Major said that, while he accepted the allegations were unsubstantiated,
as prime minister 'I must be concerned at the general perception of the
government and the capacity of ministers to carry out their work without
damaging distractions'. The resignation came 90 minutes before Mr Major told
MPs he had set up an independent commission chaired by Lord Nolan, a leading
judge, to review fundamentally the rules applying to holders of public
office.
Ministers, MPs, civil servants, council members and officers, and appointees
to quangos will all be subject to a review of their financial arrangements
and commercial relationships.
Mr Major told the Commons that he considered Mr Hamilton, who has insisted
throughout that he is innocent of any impropriety, was no longer able
effectively to carry out his ministerial duties. Earlier Mr Hamilton had
expressed regret that he had not declared details of a free stay at the
Ritz, the Paris hotel owned by Mr Fayed, in the Commons registry of members'
interests.
Last week Mr Tim Smith, a junior minister at the Northern Ireland office,
was forced to leave the government after admitting accepting payment from Mr
Fayed to table questions in the House of Commons.
The prime minister disclosed that fresh, unspecified allegations had been
levelled at Mr Hamilton since the completion yesterday of an investigation
by Sir Robin Butler, the cabinet secretary, into the charges made by Mr
Fayed.
Downing Street refused to comment on the new allegations, which were
presented to Mr Hamilton during a meeting with Mr Richard Ryder, the chief
whip, in the presence of Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry
secretary. However Tory party managers said they did not relate to Mr Fayed.
Mr Major was said also to have been furious at a statement released by Mr
Hamilton comparing his dilemma with that faced two years ago by the prime
minister over false allegations about an extra-marital affair. Amid an
astonishing series of charges and counter-charges between Mr Fayed and the
government, Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, acknowledged that he had
been one of the subjects of the investigation carried out by Sir Robin.
Mr Howard said Sir Robin's report made clear he had committed no
impropriety. He said: 'I have never been guilty of any impropriety in the
conduct of any of my responsibilities as a minister or member of
parliament.'
The report, however, did little to suppress Westminster rumours about the
past links of other Conservatives with Mr Fayed.
It said that other ministers had been questioned as a result of the
allegations first passed to Mr Major three weeks ago. Sir Robin concludes
that the allegations were either 'demonstrably false' or 'so far as I have
been able to establish are entirely unsubstantiated'.
Mr Major was attacked by Mr Blair for insisting that investigations by the
Commons privileges committee be held in private. Mr Blair accused the prime
minister of using the wider investigation to 'sweep from public view'
charges against individual MPs government members.
