<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / International Company News: Watchdog 'looks at' Microsoft
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US Justice Department's anti-trust division is 'looking at' Microsoft's
planned Dollars 1.5bn acquisition of Intuit, a personal finance software
publisher.
The department routinely reviews takeover and merger plans to ensure they do
not create anti-competitive monopolies. However, it declined to characterise
its interest in the Microsoft-Intuit transaction, saying only that it had
not undertaken 'a review'.
Microsoft said the action was routine and not related to an anti-trust
consent decree signed by the company earlier this year, or to Justice
Department monitoring of the company's activities that stems from the
consent decree.
Microsoft critics have called for the department to undertake a broad
investigation of the implications of the acquisition of Intuit. 'This deal
concentrates too much power in one company,' said Mr David Coursey, editor
of PC Letter, an industry newsletter.
'Microsoft already dominates the PC operating system market and the PC
applications software market, now they want to control the on-line service
that provides financial services. It is the aggregation of all these
interests that should cause the Justice Department to take a second look at
Microsoft.'
</TEXT>
