<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / International Company News: Higher card revenues lift
American Express
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After-tax profits from the continuing businesses of American Express climbed
18 per cent in the third quarter, due to higher revenues in its cards and
travel businesses and lower costs at IDS, its financial services subsidiary.
Net income of Dollars 369m, or 71 cents a share, compared with income on
continuing businesses of Dollars 313m, or 61 cents a share, a year ago.
Including profits from the Shearson broking firm, which has since been sold,
and Lehman Brothers, the investment bank spun off earlier this year, overall
net income in the 1993 third quarter was Dollars 420m, or 83 cents a share.
Revenues in American Express's core travel-related services area rose nearly
10 per cent, to Dollars 2.36bn.
About half the increase stemmed from an 11 per cent jump in discount
revenues from merchants, which reflected higher spending on the company's
cards.
An increase in the company's travel business, resulting partly from
acquisitions, accounted for the rest of the revenue growth. Overall, the
travel-related services businesses reported net income of Dollars 264m, up
13 per cent.
IDS had after-tax profits of Dollars 114m, up from Dollars 96m, on broadly
flat revenues of Dollars 822m. The earnings advance was partly attributable
to a Dollars 35m fall in operating costs, which the company said was due to
an absence of one-time factors which affected the 1993 period.
</TEXT>
