<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / Design of new houses attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A poll of homebuyers has found widespread dissatisfaction with the design of
the 180,000 homes built in the UK each year, Simon London writes.
The poll, by Gallup for Riba Journal, the architectural magazine, found that
60 per cent of housebuyers were dissatisfied with the design of new houses.
A similar percentage doubted whether they offered value for money and more
than 40 per cent questioned construction quality.
Other criticisms centred on the degree of choice and flexibility offered.
Nine out of ten people said housebuilders were not providing enough choice
in terms of design and more than 75 per cent wanted greater flexibility over
the layout of rooms.
The poll found that 3 per cent of the housebuying public would prefer to
live in an ultra-modern home. This suggests that there is a market for about
45,000 high-tech units each year.
</TEXT>
