<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / Tory MP failed to declare interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Conservative MP last night expressed 'regret' that he had failed to record
in the Commons register of members' interest his relationship with a
consultancy company which had employed Mr Neil Hamilton, the trade and
industry minister.
Mr Michael Colvin, the MP for Romsey and Waterside, said last night that he
had worked for a brief period for Strategy Network International.
He took up the post after Mr Hamilton, at the centre of a separate political
row over so-called 'cash for questions' allegations, joined the government
in mid-1990 and severed his connections with the consultancy.
Mr Colvin told the Financial Times that he had a 'trial run' with the
consultancy in 1991 but added: 'The relationship with the company did not
last.' The company represented a number of South African companies. Mr
Colvin had a long-standing interest in the country since he first visited it
in the 1950s and opposed the imposition of trade sanctions against the then
apartheid regime.
He said last night that his entry in the members' register for the year at
issue had been extremely detailed, including, for example, a free day's
fishing, courtesy of an industrial company.
Asked why the relationship had not been mentioned, Mr Colvin said: 'I am a
very assiduous declarer. The fact that SNI was not mentioned in that year
was an oversight that I regret.'
Mr Colvin declined, however, to comment on the size of the payment he
received, stressing that it was an 'absolute point of principle' that MPs
were not obliged to disclose such details.
</TEXT>
