<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / Army scales down patrols in N Ireland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The army has scaled down patrols in parts of Northern Ireland. Troops have
been withdrawn from the streets of Londonderry and in Strabane and Omagh,
County Tyrone.
The return to barracks by members of the King's Own Royal Border Regiment
and the Princess of Wales's Royal Regiment was confirmed yesterday.
Army Headquarters at Lisburn, County Antrim, stressed that there had been no
troop withdrawal from the province. There are just less than 18,500
soldiers, the same as before the IRA ceasefire announcement.
Soldiers have been taken off security checkpoints on the Londonderry-Donegal
border. Four checkpoints were removed at the weekend from border crossing
points in County Donegal, and another lifted in County Leitrim.
Meanwhile, nationwide raids by Irish police on terrorist targets at the
weekend provided the first evidence of opposition in republican circles to
the IRA ceasefire and the peace process.
The raids by Gardai officers in four counties near the Ulster border
resulted in the seizure of guns, ammunition, hand grenades and detonators
belonging to a previously unknown group called the Irish National Republican
Army.
The operation will underscore the Irish desire to accelerate the peace
process and harness Sinn Fein and the broader republican movement to the
peace process. The operation follows a meeting between Mr Reynolds and Mr
Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein leader, last Thursday.
A Gardai statement said the raids were directed against 'breakaway factions
such as Republican Sinn Fein and the Irish National Republican Army' which
were involved in 'criminal and subversive activity'.
Republican Sinn Fein is a splinter group established after a break with Sinn
Fein in 1986, when Mr Adams abandoned the movement's policy of boycotting
elections in the republic in a bid to raise local support.
The RSF, with the more extremist IRA offshoot, the Irish National Liberation
Army, has refused to endorse the August 31 decision to call a ceasefire.
</TEXT>
