<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / World Commodities Prices: Coffee tumbles - Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London Commodity Exchange COFFEE futures tumbled yesterday following reports
of rain in Brazilian growing areas.
The January contract ended Dollars 133 down at Dollars 3,530 a tonne after
dipping below Dollars 3,500.
As speculative selling pushed the market lower the Brazilian weather reports
'had buyers holding off until the full effect. . . on the (1995-96) crop is
known', one trader explained.
Buyers were also on the sidelines during a sluggish session at the London
Metal Exchange. Dealers said nearly all metals opted to consolidate,
absorbing speculative profit-taking and selling. They added that the
underlying trend remained upwards in most cases.
The three months COPPER price closed just 50 cents down at Dollars 2,556 a
tonne, but ALUMINIUM added Dollars 12.75 to Friday's Dollars 21.25 setback
to close at Dollars 1.740.50 a tonne.
Compiled from Reuters
