<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / Government Bonds: US Treasury long bond yield holds above 8%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The yield on the benchmark 30-year US Treasury bond held above the 8.00 per
cent mark yesterday, after flirting with that psychological barrier for the
past two weeks.
Late in the session, the long bond was  23/32 lower at 93 27/32 , with the
yield rising to 8.04 per cent, its highest level in about 2 1/2 years. At
the short end, the two-year note was down  3/32 at 99 1/2 , to yield 6.795
per cent.
There was no fresh economic news to influence sentiment, but concerns over
monetary policy, a weak dollar and the imminent influx of fresh supply meant
that the bearish tone established last week would not budge.
In light of last week's data, the market was convinced the Federal Reserve
would lift short-term interest rates at its November 15 policy-making
session, and they were trying to gauge how that would affect their
commitments.
Those calculations had a negative impact on trading on the day before the
Treasury is to auction Dollars 17.25bn in new two-year notes. The auction
will be followed by the sale tomorrow of Dollars 11bn in five-year notes.
The new issues may prove difficult for the market to absorb. Some analysts
were betting that the Fed will decide to lift rates aggressively in the
coming weeks, a development which would undercut the value of the new
securities. A fresh decline in the dollar against the D-Mark and yen
reinforced the pessimism.
The selling yesterday came across the board, not just at the short end. As
the long bond's prices fell, the yield climbed back over the 8.00 per cent
mark, where it has attracted buying interest in the past. But yesterday, the
higher levels prevailed.
Shrugging off encouraging inflation data in Germany, European government
bonds were depressed by continued weakness in US Treasuries and ended a
listless session weaker across the board.
In addition to the bearish sentiment spreading from across the Atlantic, the
prospect of fresh supply this week in the German, UK, Japanese, Italian, Ecu
and US markets, and continued investor abstinence, put a damper on prices.
German government bonds ended the day about 1/3 point weaker, unimpressed by
reports that consumer prices in North Rhine-Westphalia and Baden-Wurttemberg
rose by only 0.1 per cent in the month to mid-October. Although the news
gave bunds a brief lift, the gains were not sustainable.
'When you get good news and prices don't rise, that usually indicates that a
market wants to go down,' said a Frankfurt bund dealer.
In after-hours trading, the December bund future on Liffe breached key
technical support at 89.50, which does not bode well for the near term, a
dealer said. It ended at 89.46, down 0.36 points on the day.
In spite of their unimpressive performance, bunds are still the best bet in
current bond market conditions, said Mr Adrian James, bond strategist at
NatWest Markets. 'Bunds may not necessarily do well in absolute terms, but
they still tend to outperform in this environment,' he said.
Sweden was one of the few markets which managed to out-shine bunds, lifted
by the unexpected success of the government's latest bond auction, where all
the paper in both tranches offered was snapped up by a single buyer.
This sparked another sharp rise in prices, pushing the yield on the
benchmark nine-year bond down 16 basis points to 10.71 per cent.
The yield gap over bunds narrowed 22 basis points to 316 basis points. It
was as wide as 360 basis points in the middle of last week, but has been
sharply eroded by the Swedish market's strong performance in recent days.
After its speedy contraction, the spread looks 'dangerous,' warned Mr Graham
McDevitt, bond strategist at Paribas Capital Markets.
'We have entered the red zone,' he said, pointing to the risks facing the
Swedish market: the European Union referendum on November 13, another
increase in interest rates, and continued uncertainty on the fiscal front.
UK gilts fell by more than  1/2 point, dragged lower by the US market and
weighed down further by the prospect of Pounds 2.5bn of new supply at
tomorrow's gilt auction. However, dealers said they expected the issue to
meet solid demand since it was next year's new five-year benchmark.
The December long gilt futures contract slipped by points to 101 15/32.
</TEXT>
