<HEADLINE>
FT  25 OCT 94 / International Company News: Record Caterpillar result in
spite of UAW strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Caterpillar, the US producer of construction machinery, reported record
sales and profits in the third quarter, in spite of a continuing strike by
its United Autoworkers' union employees.
The company said earnings jumped on a 19 per cent increase in sales of
engines and machinery, and that the strike had no significant impact on its
bottom line.
Caterpillar earned Dollars 244m, or Dollars 1.20 a share, in the quarter, up
from Dollars 142m, or 72 cents, in the corresponding 1993 quarter. Sales
were Dollars 3.51bn, compared with Dollars 2.81bn in the third quarter last
year.
News of the results drove Caterpillar's share price up Dollars 2 to close at
Dollars 58 1/4 on Wall Street, where analysts had expected the company to
return 85 cents a share.
For the first nine months the company earned Dollars 676m, or Dollars 3.32 a
share, on sales of Dollars 10.4bn, compared with last year's Dollars 533m,
or Dollars 2.64 a share, on sales of Dollars 8.4bn.
The strike, which began on June 21 and covers 14,000 employees at eight
Caterpillar plants in the Midwest, left nearly 6,000 salaried and management
employees to man the assembly lines during the quarter. The company also
brought in contract workers, called back retirees and hired new full-time
employees to meet production schedules.
The costs of alternative labour offset any savings garnered from not paying
striking employees, the company said.
Mr James Owens, Caterpillar's chief financial officer, said the company was
prepared to continue to operate in this mode indefinitely. Mr Owens said the
company was not asking customers to delay deliveries, but that shipments of
many products were being made based on the urgency of customer needs.
Caterpillar said that it expected a strong fourth quarter and forecast
higher worldwide sales in 1995.
